# Constraint Satisfaction Problem (CSP):
# A CSP is a problem where a solution must satisfy
# a set of constraints or rules.

# Examples of CSP:
# 1. N-Queens Problem
# 2. Sudoku
# 3. Graph Coloring
# 4. Timetable Scheduling

# N-Queens Problem:
# The N-Queens problem is a classic CSP problem.
# The objective is to place N queens on an N x N chessboard
# such that no queen attacks another queen.

# Rules of N-Queens:
# 1. Only one queen can be placed in one row.
# 2. Only one queen can be placed in one column.
# 3. No two queens can be placed on same diagonal.

# Queen Movement in Chess:
# A queen can move:
# 1. Horizontally
# 2. Vertically
# 3. Diagonally

# Therefore, while placing queens,
# all these directions must be checked.

# State Space Tree:
# The problem can be represented using a state space tree.
# Each level represents a row of chessboard.
# Each branch represents a possible column position.

# Backtracking:
# Backtracking is a recursive problem-solving technique.

# Working of Backtracking:
# 1. Choose a possible solution.
# 2. Check whether it is valid.
# 3. If valid, continue further.
# 4. If invalid, go back and try another option.

# In N-Queens:
# If a queen placement causes conflict later,
# the queen is removed and another position is tried.

# Advantages of Backtracking:
# 1. Simple and easy to implement.
# 2. Reduces unnecessary computations.
# 3. Finds valid solution systematically.

# Disadvantages of Backtracking:
# 1. Recursive calls increase for large N.
# 2. Time complexity is high.

# Branch and Bound:
# Branch and Bound is an optimization technique.

# Branch:
# Trying different possible choices.

# Bound:
# Avoiding paths that cannot produce valid solution.

# In N-Queens:
# Arrays are used to quickly check:
# 1. Occupied columns
# 2. Occupied upper diagonals
# 3. Occupied lower diagonals

# This reduces repeated checking
# and improves execution speed.

# Arrays Used:
# leftRow:
# Stores whether a column already contains queen.

# upperDiagonal:
# Stores occupied upper diagonals.

# lowerDiagonal:
# Stores occupied lower diagonals.

# Why Branch and Bound is Faster:
# Instead of scanning entire chessboard,
# arrays directly tell whether position is safe.

# Recursion:
# Recursion means a function calling itself.

# In N-Queens:
# Recursive function places queens row by row.

# Base Condition:
# When row becomes equal to N,
# it means all queens are placed successfully.

# Time Complexity:
# Worst case time complexity is approximately O(N!)

# Space Complexity:
# O(N^2) for chessboard storage.

# Applications of N-Queens:
# 1. Artificial Intelligence
# 2. Game development
# 3. Resource allocation
# 4. Scheduling problems

# Graph Coloring:
# Graph coloring is another CSP problem.

# Objective:
# Assign colors to graph vertices such that
